<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06346179 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06346179 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CONSUMER; QA  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Q  I've been trying to reach the Franchise Tax Board's toll-free number (800)852-5711 but get a constant busy signal. Our business needs the payroll taxdeduction forms.;   -- A. McLaughlin, Morgan Hill  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FRANCHISE TAX BOARD TAXES NO BUSINESSES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Action Line  </MEMO><TEXT>  A  Surprise! The FTB doesn't want your money. Although the FTB sends out stateincome tax refunds, it doesn't collect money from businesses. You must contactthe Employment Development Department, 107 E. Gish Road, San Jose (408)452-7175 for forms to send in both employee income tax and state disabilitywithheld. An FTB spokesman did confirm that its phone line has been bombardedbecause the department just mailed out 300,000 notices to people who havenever before filed with the FTB.;   Refund and red tape; Q  On June 15, mywife's mother had a stroke in Boston and I called Trans World Airlines to seeif I could use my Frequent Flyer mileage to cover an emergency trip thatnight. The TWA reservation clerk said yes and booked a 9 p.m. flight for mywife. At the ticket counter, we were told they could not issue the ticket. Ipurchased a one-way ticket as per instructions and was told to call FrequentFlyer on Monday to get a refund for the ticket. I called the Frequent Flyerdivision on Monday and was told there would be no refund but that we stillcould submit an official claim form. My Frequent Flyer mileage was applied tomy wife's return trip home. We did file a claim but have heard nothing fromTWA.;   -- J.L.F., San Jose; A  TWA has no refund file for you, says B.A.Blessing, a TWA refund specialist. Blessing needs you to send him somephotocopies. He is sending you a letter detailing what he needs to begin theclaim. As soon as you send the information to him, a claim will be processed.;  How to help the needy; Q  I have some old eyeglasses from my daughter thatare just sitting around. Is there a group that can use them?;   -- S. Snyder,San Jose;   Is there a group that collects used clothing and furniture andactually gives them to the homeless people free of charge? I don't want togive to a group that ends up selling these items.;   -- J. Wade, San Jose;  Do you know of any groups that can use used stamps, cents-off coupons andBetty Crocker coupons?;   -- M. Larsen, Milpitas; A  We'd like to hear fromcharitable organizations wanting used items. If your group wants eyeglasses,clothing, furniture, stamps, cents-off or Betty Crocker coupons, greetingcards, television sets, old trophies or telephone books, call a special ActionLine number (408) 920-5437 by noon Thursday. We'll publish a list of theresponding groups within a few days. We'll need the full name of theorganization, address, phone number and contact person.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911211  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  476  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, December 11, 199100346179,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>